Wiring / Pin diagram (text + ASCII)

Summary pins used (on ESP32 DevKit):

3.3V — power to sensors (DHT11 VCC, DS18B20 VCC, optionally soil probe VCC if module supports 3.3V)

GND — common ground (all sensors + buzzer)

DHT11 data → GPIO4

DS18B20 data → GPIO15 with 4.7kΩ pull-up between data and 3.3V

Soil AO (HW-080/AO) → GPIO35 (ADC1_CH7) (analog)

LDR voltage divider → middle node → GPIO34 (ADC1_CH6) (analog)

LDR + fixed resistor, typical 100k or 10k depending on bright/dim conditions

Buzzer (+) → GPIO27, (–) → GND (active buzzer assumed)

ASCII (simplified):

ESP32 DevKit          Sensor / Module
-----------           ---------------
3.3V    --------------- VCC (DHT11, DS18B20 VCC, module VCC if 3.3V)
GND     --------------- GND (all sensors + buzzer)
GPIO4   --------------- DHT11 DATA
GPIO15  --------------- DS18B20 DATA -----[4.7kΩ]----- 3.3V
GPIO35  --------------- HW-080 AO (soil analog)
GPIO34  --------------- LDR voltage divider (middle node)
GPIO27  --------------- BUZZER +   (BUZZER - -> GND)


LDR wiring (voltage divider):

One LDR leg → 3.3V

Other LDR leg → analog pin (GPIO34) and to a fixed resistor (e.g., 100k) that goes to GND.

ADC reads middle node; larger ADC value = more light (depends on resistor choice). Calibrate.

HW-080 (YL-69)

This module has VCC, GND, AO and DO (digital). Use AO for analog percentage measurement. If board expects 5V VCC, test with 3.3V and check readings — many modules work at 3.3V. If you must use 5V, do not connect probe AO directly to ESP32 ADC without level shifting (ADC max ~3.3V)


ESP32 DevKit          Sensor / Module
-----------           ---------------
3.3V    --------------- VCC (DHT11, DS18B20 VCC, module VCC if 3.3V)
GND     --------------- GND (all sensors + buzzer)
GPIO4   --------------- DHT11 DATA
GPIO15  --------------- DS18B20 DATA -----[4.7kΩ]----- 3.3V
GPIO35  --------------- HW-080 AO (soil analog)
GPIO34  --------------- LDR voltage divider (middle node)
GPIO27  --------------- BUZZER +   (BUZZER - -> GND)

To connect a DS18B20 sensor to an ESP32, connect the sensor's VCC pin to the
ESP32's 3.3V pin, the GND pin to a ground pin, and the data (DQ) pin to an 
ESP32 GPIO pin (e.g., GPIO4). You must also add a 4.7kΩ pull-up resistor
between the data pin and the 3.3V power line